Mbit's Btobb, Sboonb Ploob.\nI '\"v.\n-IL I I\ny. 4 N w. JH \u25a0_ JK;\ntwo injured persons, Mrs. Flora Miller,\n60, and Ora Paxson, 22.\nThree Investigations of the blast, be\nlieved in mast circles to have resulted\nfrom the explosion of natural gas mains\nunder the building, was under way\ntoday. A coroner\u2019s jury has been sum\nmoned to conduct an inquest.\nProperty loss Is believed to total\n$450,000.\nSNIACKOVERBOOM TOWN\nArkansas Village Increases Popu\nlation 2,540 Per Cent.\nSMACXQVER, Ark., May 10 (/P).\nHere\u2019s one for civic boosters. In 1920\nSmackover was a railroad flag stop with\nplenty of iresh air and a population or\ni less than 100.\nThe 1930 census gives it 2.544 in\nhabitants or an increase of 2,540 per\nI cent.\nSix months after the 1920 census an\noil boom began and at one time it had\nan estimated population of 10,000. It\nstill is an important center for well\ndrillers\n0\nDuring the recent gale off the coast\nof Brittany lamps of several light\nhouses were extinguished:\nBOY PATROLS CUT\nDEATH OF CHILDREN\nA. A. A. Safety Committee Finds\n33 Per Cent Reduction in Fatal\nAccidents in Capital.\nThe schoolboy patrols, which stand\nguard at street Intersections near the j\nCapital\u2019s schools, have brought about i\na reduction of 33 per cent In fatal acci-1\ni dents to .children or school age since\n1926, it was announced yesterday by\nthe safety committee of the restrict\ndivision the American Automobile\nAssociation.\nAt a meet tig presided over by Isaac\nGans chairman, the committee re\nviewed the work of approximately 2,000\nboys who serve in 158 patrols in the\nDistrict. In 1926, when the patrols\nwere organized, there were 15 fatal ac\n-1 cidents to children of school age. Dur\ning 1929 there were 10 such accidents.\nThere is one boy patrolman for each\n40 children, based on a school popula\ntion of 79,000.\nThe action of Maj. Henry G. Pratt,\nsuperintendent of police, in assigning\n13 policemen to aid in instructing the\nschool patrolmen, was commended by\nthe committee, which meets to discuss\nthe formulation of general policies look\ning to highway safety. Attending the\nmeeting were Selden M. Ely. vice chair\nman: Edward J. Murphy, William John\nEynon, H. V. Schreiber, A. W. Carr,\nmember of the D. C. advisory board: j\nCharles P. Clark, general manager of\nthe A A. A., and Howard M. Starling.\nA. A. A. director of safety.\nCLUB FIXES ELECTION\nSt. Mark's Parish Men Decide on\nSecond Thursday of October.\nAt a meeting of the Men\u2019s Club of i\n31. Mark's Parish, held in the parish i\nhall. Third and A streets southeast.\nThursday night, it was decided to hold j\nthe annual election of officers at the I\nnext session of the body, which will i\nbe the second Thursday of October.\nDiscussion of the activity of the club\nduring the Winter months featured the\nmeeting Thursday. David Meade Lea,\npresident of the club, presided at the\nmeeting, which was largely attended.\nALEXANDER QUITS EGYPT\nAND RETURNS TO VIENNA\nCount's Engagement to Rumania*\nPrincess Recently Was Broken.\nIlesna Goes to Jerusalem.\n1 By the Associated Press.\nALEXANDER. Egypt. May 10.\u2014Count\nAlexander of Hochberg, whose engage\nment to Princess Ileana of Rumania.\u2019\nrecently was broken, left here today for\nVienna.\nPrincess Ileana. who with her mother.\nQueen Marie of Rumania, had bt'X\nenjoying a visit in ingypt, left Cairn f.\u00ab-\nI Jerusalem on April 5\nj After the visit of Queen Marie and\nj the princess to Luxor in March and\nwhile the princess still was wearing an\nI engagement rin\u00df, she decided to remain\nat the Rumanian legation in Cairo.\nI Her mother went home at the end of\nI April.\nThe prince arrived at Alexander from\n1 \u00ab\u00ab\u00bbi)les March 5 and paid a short visit\nlto Cairo. Whether he met his form\u2019r\nfiancee was not learned, but it was be\nlieved that no meeting occurred.\nAmerican tractors are being used on\nfarms in Spain.\nA-5","height":"25455","width":"19839"}}
